# Single definition site for the integration-test credentials.
#
# Consumed by:
#   - docker-compose.yml   (keycloak service, via `env_file:`) — the variables are
#     injected into the Keycloak container's runtime environment, where the
#     `--import-realm` placeholder substitution resolves them.
#   - keycloak/*-realm.json — via PLAIN `${VAR}` placeholders (see the syntax note below).
#   - scripts/lib-start-processors.sh — sources this file for the NiFi token fetch.
#   - check-status.sh, run-and-deploy.sh, start-keycloak.sh — source this file so the
#     credentials they print stay in agreement with the ones the realm actually uses.
#   - IntegrationTestSupport.java — parses this file so the Java ITs authenticate with
#     the same values the realm was imported with.
#   - e-2-e-playwright/utils/constants.js — parses this file so the Playwright suite
#     authenticates with the same values. Environment variables still override, but
#     there are no hardcoded fallbacks: an undefined credential fails loudly at
#     startup rather than silently authenticating as a default user.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Placeholder syntax in realm JSON — PLAIN `${VAR}`, never `${env.VAR}`
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Verified empirically against quay.io/keycloak/keycloak:26.2.5 with --import-realm:
#
#   ${VAR}      -> substituted from the container environment.   (authentication
#                  with the substituted value returns HTTP 200)
#   ${env.VAR}  -> NOT substituted; imported as the LITERAL string "${env.VAR}",
#                  which then becomes the user's actual password.
#
# The `${env.VAR}` spelling is the intuitive one and is what other products
# (e.g. WildFly) use, which makes it a trap: it fails SILENTLY. A realm imported
# with an unsubstituted placeholder yields a user whose password is the literal
# text "${env.TEST_USER_PASSWORD}", and the resulting breakage presents as an
# authentication failure rather than an import failure. Always use PLAIN ${VAR}.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Known coupling: the NiFi password is ALSO pinned as a bcrypt hash
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# nifi/conf/login-identity-providers.xml stores the NiFi login password as a
# bcrypt hash, not as plain text, so it cannot be driven from this file.
# Changing TEST_USER_PASSWORD below therefore does NOT change the NiFi login
# password — the hash in that file must be regenerated to match, or NiFi
# authentication (and the token fetch in scripts/lib-start-processors.sh) will
# start failing. The username in that file is the plain literal `testUser` and
# must be kept in agreement with TEST_USER_NAME below.

# ── Keycloak realm: oauth_integration_tests ────────────────────────────────
# testUser and limitedUser are TWO DISTINCT users that happen to share the same
# password. They differ in their realm roles: testUser has [user, read] while
# limitedUser has [user] only, which is what the scope-restriction tests rely on.
# Keep them as separate entries — do not collapse them into a single credential.
TEST_USER_NAME=testUser
TEST_USER_PASSWORD=drowssap
LIMITED_USER_NAME=limitedUser
LIMITED_USER_PASSWORD=drowssap

# ── Keycloak realm: other_realm (different RSA key pair for signature tests) ──
OTHER_USER_NAME=otherUser
OTHER_USER_PASSWORD=drowssap
OTHER_CLIENT_SECRET=otherClientSecretValue123456789

# ── Keycloak bootstrap admin ───────────────────────────────────────────────
KC_BOOTSTRAP_ADMIN_USERNAME=admin
KC_BOOTSTRAP_ADMIN_PASSWORD=admin
